= Lausanne Conference Concludes

After weeks of difficult negotiations with the <span style="color: #0A3161;">Western</span> <span style="color: #C8102E;">Allies</span>, the German delegation at the Lausanne Conference has finally secured a result—though not the one it had hoped for. When talks hit a snag, Papen made a dramatic offer: a military alliance with <span style="color: #002654;">France</span>, sealed by an exchange of general staff officers. This only outraged the <span style="color: #C8102E;">British</span> and deepened <span style="color: #002654;">French</span> mistrust.

<span style="color: #C8102E;">British</span> Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald tried to salvage the negotiations by proposing the repeal of disarmament clauses. But <span style="color: #002654;">French</span> Prime Minister Édouard Herriot rejected this outright—refusing any political discussions and treating Germany’s offer as an admission it could still pay. Backed into a corner, Papen’s delegation was left with no option but to offer a final payment of three billion marks—in exchange for nothing.

