Germany’s reparations burden has been slashed by 90%, with no payments due for another three years. This eases the strain on the national budget and gives the government new room to maneuver on monetary and fiscal policy.

Unfortunately for Papen, this does little to ease the near-universal hatred of his government. The <span style="color: #7A3C00;">far</span>-<span style="color: #3E88B3;">right</span> has denounced the treaty as a failure, outraged by his inability to secure any political or military concessions. Meanwhile, the <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span> parties and press have handed the credit to Brüning, who laid the groundwork for the conference in the first place. This development would've certainly been more impactful if Brüning had remained in office.

Papen’s tarnished reputation among the <span style="color: #0A3161;">Western</span> <span style="color: #C8102E;">Allies</span> has severely undermined Germany’s standing at the Geneva Disarmament Conference. With many now convinced that militarism has triumphed in Berlin, Schleicher’s efforts to negotiate military parity are likely to face steep resistance.